A 7-year-old boy presents with his third episode of mild acute pancreatitis over the past 12 months. Each episode resolved with conservative management, and he is currently asymptomatic between episodes. Prior workup included normal abdominal ultrasound showing no gallstones or anatomic anomalies, normal triglyceride levels, and unremarkable family history. Physical examination and routine laboratories are normal. What is the most appropriate next diagnostic test to identify the underlying etiology?\
\
A. Bile microcrystal analysis  \
B. Genetic screening for pancreatitis-associated mutations  \
C. Evaluation for celiac disease  \
D. Metabolic screening with serum ammonia and urine organic acids  \
E. Stool studies for ova and parasites  \
